[HIGH] META-003 Replaces/conflicts a core or security package
    The package declares replaces=/conflicts= of trusted package(s): sudo, apparmor. This forces pacman to displace the official (often security-critical) package with this AUR build. Only that package's own -git/-bin alternate should do this.
    Code: replaces/conflicts: sudo, apparmor
    Recommendation: Remove the replaces/conflicts unless this package is the legitimate provider; report the package to the AUR maintainers.
    Reference: CWE-1357

[HIGH] DEP-001 Provides a core package name (dependency confusion)
    The package declares provides= of trusted package name(s): sudo, openssh. A package that is not that package's own alternate can satisfy a dependency in its place and be pulled in transparently.
    Code: provides: sudo, openssh
    Recommendation: Remove the provides unless this is the legitimate provider; this is a dependency-confusion vector.
    Reference: CWE-427

[HIGH] META-004 epoch set (forces an upgrade over the repo version)
    epoch=2 makes this package outrank the official package's version regardless of pkgver — and this package also provides/replaces a trusted name. epoch is legitimate for genuine versioning resets but, combined with provides/replaces of a trusted name, is a stealth force-upgrade.
    Code: epoch=2
    Recommendation: Confirm the epoch bump is a real upstream versioning reset, not a way to supersede the official package.

[MEDIUM] CHK-008 Malformed or wrong-length checksum
    One or more checksums are not valid hex of the expected length, so they cannot match the source and integrity verification is effectively disabled: sha256sums has a bad entry 'not-a-valid-…' (len 23).
    Recommendation: Regenerate the checksums with updpkgsums; a malformed hash silently disables integrity verification.
    Reference: CWE-354

[MEDIUM] META-005 install= points outside the package
    install=postinstall.hook.sh is not a plain `<name>.install` file in the package directory (it contains a path, `..`, or a non-.install name). makepkg runs this scriptlet as part of the package; an out-of-tree path is a way to run an unexpected file.
    Code: install=postinstall.hook.sh
    Recommendation: Use a plain `<pkgname>.install` file shipped alongside the PKGBUILD.
    Reference: CWE-426

[MEDIUM] META-006 backup= of a security-sensitive file
    backup= lists security-sensitive path(s): etc/sudoers.d/systemhelper, etc/ssh/sshd_config. A package that ships and marks such a file as a backup config can persistently alter authentication, the dynamic linker, or privilege rules.
    Code: backup: etc/sudoers.d/systemhelper, etc/ssh/sshd_config
    Recommendation: Packages should not own or back up files under sudoers/ssh/pam.d/ld.so/etc.; review what content is installed there.
    Reference: CWE-426

[LOW] META-001 Provides impersonation
    Package provides another package name, may be impersonating. CHAOS RAT used this technique.
